;Superposition:
To superimpose, the following command is used:
<code>match #0:1.A@C21,C20,O20,C17,C16,C15,C14,C13,C12,C11,C9,C8,C7,C6,C5,C4,C3,O3,C2,C1,C10,C19,C18 #1@C1,C2,O1,C3,C4,C5,C6,C7,C8,C9,C10,C11,C12,C13,C14,C15,C16,O2,C17,C18,C19,C20,C21</code>

[[File:prog_sup.jpg|500px]]

It looks like the superposition at the acyl tail is the worst, which may reduce the quality of the superposition of rigid tetra-ring system.

So I instead removed the acyl atoms from superposition:
<code>match #0:1.A@C17,C16,C15,C14,C13,C12,C11,C9,C8,C7,C6,C5,C4,C3,O3,C2,C1,C10,C19,C18 #1@C3,C4,C5,C6,C7,C8,C9,C10,C11,C12,C13,C14,C15,C16,O2,C17,C18,C19,C20,C21</code>

... which resulted in much better alignment of the rigid rings.

It is apparent that the superposition is quite good. The greatest deviation occurs at the acetyl tail.

Perhaps due to a slightly different conformation of the five-membered ring and the acyl tail, the methyl attached to the five-membered ring also seems to noticeably deviate from my structural model.

